{
  "doc_id": "10905",
  "text": "Mitochondrial-derived ROS have gained substantial interest in the regulation of HIF-1 induction and activation. The hypoxic activation of HIF-1␣ has been shown by two independent groups to be regulated by mtROS [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Additionally, a nonhypoxic activator of HIF-1, thrombopoietin (TPO), has been shown to control HIF-1␣ levels through the generation of mtROS [CITATION_3] . Although the NADPH oxidase has classically been shown as the primary ROS generator in VSMCs and noxROS to be involved in different signaling pathways, our study now identifies mtROS as an essential intermediate for PHD inactivation, HIF-1␣ stabilization, and HIF-1 activation when VSMCs are stimulated with Ang II. Taken together, these studies suggest that mitochondrial ROS are a common intermediate signal transducer between hypoxic and nonhypoxic stimuli leading to the activation of HIF-1.",
